%U A339263 4,5,8,3,1,4,8,1,5,5,5,3,1,5,0,1,9,4,5
%N A339263 Decimal expansion of the conjecturally maximum possible volume of a polyhedron with 11 vertices inscribed in the unit sphere.
%C A339263 The polyhedron (see linked illustration) with a symmetry group of order 4 has a vertex in the north pole on its axis of symmetry. The remaining 10 vertices are diametrically opposite in pairs relative to this axis of symmetry. The polar vertex has vertex degree 6, 8 vertices have vertex degree 5, 2 vertices have vertex degree 4.
%C A339263 This allocation seems to be the best possible approximation of a medial distribution of the vertex degrees, which is a known necessary condition for maximum volume. Of the 25 possible triangulations with vertex degree >= 4, all the others have more than 2 vertices with vertex degree 4, which leads to more pointed corners and therefore smaller volumes.
%C A339263 From _Natalia L. Skirrow_, Apr 14 2026: (Start)
%C A339263 Under symmetry, vertices are placed in four equivalence classes.
%C A339263 Polar: (1,0,0), degree 6.
%C A339263 A (2): ( 0.4896137683977283185743948709816, +-0.8719394232372886891423869823160, 0), degree 4.
%C A339263 B (2): (-0.5205567155907513088935689248032, +-0.8538270936515013477953585133062, 0), degree 5.
%C A339263 C (2): (-0.8037055502923919636760197900010,  0, +-0.595027216544926969906810550644), degree 5.
%C A339263 D (4): ( 0.2039058592439469808439143858004, +-0.4959591806792675848771562922995, +-0.8440656915583865219655696349822), degree 5.
%C A339263 We have that B_x = 2*a_x^2-1 and B_y = 2*a_x*a_y, reducing the optimization to only three parameters.
%C A339263 The volume is algebraic with degree 100, though its minpoly's odd terms have coefficient 0, so its square has degree 50. Unfortunately, the Galois group is S_50, so no solution with radicals can exist.
%C A339263 (End)
%H A339263 R. H. Hardin, N. J. A. Sloane and W. D. Smith, <a href="http://neilsloane.com/maxvolumes">Maximal Volume Spherical Codes</a>.
%H A339263 Cosmia Nebula and Natalia L. Skirrow, <a href="/A339263/a339263.py.txt">Python program</a> to compute terms via Newton's method (2026).
%H A339263 Cosmia Nebula and Natalia L. Skirrow, <a href="/A339263/a339263.txt">minimal polynomial for the volume's square</a>
%H A339263 Hugo Pfoertner, <a href="https://www.randomwalk.de/sphere/volmax/pages/11.htm">Visualization of Polyhedron</a>, (1999).
